And the wall collapsed …
<s>Here is a quiz for history enthusiasts: 20 years ago, the year 1989 was a fateful one marked by three events that all occurred on June 4.
<s>Which one do you remember best and which one had the greatest consequence for the planet?
a) The bloody suppression of Tiananmen Square
b) The death of Ayatollah Khomeini in Iran
c) Les élections en Pologne
Peu nombreux sont ceux qui répondent c).
Car les événements de Pékin et le décès de Khomeini qui ont fait grand bruit ont éclipsé la victoire du célèbre syndicat d'opposition Solidarność lors des premières élections libres en Europe de l'Est depuis 1946.
Pourtant, rien n'a contribué davantage à l'effondrement du communisme en Europe - et par conséquent à la réfondation de l'ordre international post-guerre.
Il y aura au cours des prochains mois toutes sortes de célébrations de la fin du communisme, notamment l'anniversaire de la chute du mur de Berlin en novembre 1989.
For many people, it was an hour of glory, symbolic of the Western victory at the end of the Cold War, a victory whose origins are unknown.
But having witnessed the collapse of the Eastern Bloc from the beginning, one realizes that the process was long and complex.
The election in Poland was a turning point, the moment when the movement in favor of change became irreversible.
It had gained strength after a summer of strikes, when the Communist leader in charge of Poland, General Jaruzelski, believed that the country's economic problems were too serious for him to face them alone.
Why not call on the Polish opposition, he asked himself – if not to find a solution, at least to share the responsibility for the situation?
After six months of bargaining, he concluded a historic agreement: there would be free and fair legislative elections, and Solidarnosc could participate.
Communist leaders (no more than Solidarnosc) never even considered for a moment that they might lose.
Even in their darkest nightmares, they did not imagine that they would be chased from power.
Yet, that is what happened.
Retrospectively, it is surprising that there were any doubts.
Solidarność ran its campaign with boldness.
A famous parody poster from a classic Western, The Train Will Blow Its Whistle Three Times, was a huge success: on it, Gary Cooper holds a ballot instead of a revolver, playing the role of the sheriff.
June 4 was the day of judgment.
On this bright Sunday morning, as spring was giving birth to summer, voters sent the Polish communists to the slaughter.
On their last day in power, the Polish communists resorted to a final perversion that turned into an unintentional self-demeaning act.
They designed a voting system where instead of selecting the candidates of their choice, Poles had to cross out the names of those they didn't want—basically, all the communists listed on the ballots.
Everywhere you looked, people were getting rid of the hated autocrats.
This was finally the popular uprising that Poland had been waiting for for so long—the revenge following December 1980, when Jaruzelski declared martial law, banned Solidarność, and threw its leaders in prison.
The revolution with a pen!
When wielded with style, the pen, which eventually triumphed over the sword, becomes the weapon of a glorious revenge.
Certain voters were tearing up their ballots, effectively decapitating the old regime with a single, effective stroke.
Others savored the moment, perhaps lighting a cigarette while crossing out names on the ballots.
"He put my cousin in prison," Pfft!, "That apparatchik got rich off our shortages," Pfft!
Pfft!
However, the communist campaign passed almost unnoticed.
In Warsaw, only two government candidates bothered to put up posters.
The rest relied on their monopoly in the media to get their message across: "Vote for Lezek, a good communist."
We can say that the regime recognized its defeat with remarkable grace.
The day after the elections, at three in the afternoon, Jaruzelski gathered the main party officials to tell them: "Our defeat is total," we need to find a political solution.
He meant that there would be no violence or rigging; the communists would have to live with the election results.
Twenty years later, I am still perplexed.
Those of us who covered Eastern Europe knew that Solidarność would win.
We also knew that this peaceful victory would be an example for the rest of the Eastern bloc.
The Polish election was extremely encouraging for anticommunists everywhere.
Thanks to Poland, what seemed impossible just a few days earlier suddenly became achievable.
There were other signs.
In May, reformist Hungarians began to dismantle the barbed wire erected on the border with Austria—a hole in the Iron Curtain.
In Moscow, Mikhail Gorbachev spoke of a "Common European House" and rejected Brezhnev's interventionist doctrine.
Yet when the wall fell, political leaders and experts unanimously recognized: "We saw nothing coming."
The Cold War lasted so long that any change seemed impossible—until the day freedom exploded.
